To identify the detail morphology and the coating of rGQDs, transmission electron microscopy (TEM) was performed and the results are shown in Fig. 2
                     . Fig. 2a shows that some Fe2O3 nanorods-like interconnect each other and construct the worm-like Fe2O3 nanostructure electrodes. The diameter of the single Fe2O3 nanorod is around 66.2 nm. The lattice resolution TEM image suggests that the spacing of lattice fringe is ∼2.7 Å, which agrees well with the {110} lattice spacing of α-Fe2O3. To self-assemble GOQDs onto Fe2O3, the bare Fe2O3 electrodes were immersed into GOQDs aqueous solution (pH = 7). The isoelectric point (IEP) of 9.3 makes the surface of Fe2O3 positively charged [30]. Therefore there is strong electrostatic interaction between the positive charged Fe2O3 surface with −OH+ and negative charged GOQDs with –COO− for a spontaneous self-assembly of GOQDs fully onto Fe2O3 (Scheme 1
                     ). After the thermal reduction, a ∼5.15 nm thick layer of rGQDs can be observed (Fig. 2d). On the Fe2O3 zone, the single crystalline character also can be identified (Fig. 2e). In Fig. 2g, the ∼3.4 Å lattice spacing can be observed from rGQDs layer, while the control image (Fig. 2f) just displays a clean and smooth edge. The lattice spacing as shown in Fig. 2f also indicates the [110] oriented growth of α-Fe2O3 nanorods.
